📸: @brandon_hannan_photography⁣

⚠️ Not to be confused with an Algae Octopus, the Hairy octopus gets it's name from the hundreds of tiny skin spikes they have on their body that resemble hair blowing in the water. 
⁣
👾 They are MUCH smaller than most anticipate, this one is only an inch long! (Full grown they’re smaller than a golf ball!) 
⁣
🤔 Have you ever heard of this species?⁣
⁣
😅 We like to affectionately refer to them as the Chewbactopus LOL⁣
⁣
🗣 Here is what Videographer Brandon had to say... ⁣
⁣
🤩 “To say I am excited is an understatement. This video below is of a Hairy Octopus. To my knowledge I don’t think anyone has found them here in Okinawa, Japan. This is a bucket list cephalopod for me. I spent 35 mins watching and photographing this guy. Truly amazing this guy is only 1in. in size.” ⁣
⁣
Know someone who would think this lil’critter is cute? Tag em below for #OCTOpusMonth! ⁣

🗣 Tag some friends below and spend the weekend drawing octopuses! ⁣
⁣
OctoNation & @briankesinger Kesinger got together a couple weeks ago and put on a how-to class for beginners! Just search OctoNation on YouTube! These are some of the drawings from class! ⁣⁣
⁣
⚠️ Make sure you tag #OctoNation & #BrianKesinger so we can see your work! ⁣
⁣
👨‍🎨 @BrianKesinger is an award winning story artist, illustrator and author. His 20+ year career at Disney has spanned both hand drawn and CG animated films from Tarzan to Frozen 2. In addition to Brian's film work, he has also become a celebrated author and illustrator of several books that showcase his style, wit and ability to tell engaging stories in original ways. His artistic journey has lead him to find an additional home with Marvel Comics and Lucasfilm where he blends his animation background with the comic art form to create dazzling and expressive art! ⁣
⁣
Long Story Short— Brian is a LEGEND! (Also- he’s the youngest person to have been hired to Disney animation studios at the age of 18) ⁣⁣
⁣
If you read this far comment “Lezz draw some octoz!” & tag some buddies ✏️ 🐙⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣

Cirrate octopuses have a small, internal “U” saddle shaped shell to support the two big flappy fins on their head! ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
@NautilusLive captured this footage while diving 1580m deep (.98 miles) along a seamount located southwest of Baker Island (almost halfway between Hawaii and Australia)⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
🥇 This species has the deepest known living cephalopod record — being spotted at 7,000m deep (4.35 miles deep!) ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⚠️ It’s name? Cirroteuthis Muelleri— it’s one of the largest cirrate octopuses, growing to a length of 1.5 metres (4.9 ft)⁣⁣
⁣⁣
🐘: so it’s basically a giant dumbo octopus! 🤩⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
👗 you’ve probably noticed that Cirrate octopuses have quite the dress! Observe how the webbing can extend to the very tips of their arms! ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
🤩 The name Cirrate comes from the long slender  hair-like structures called ‘cirri’ that MIGHT aid these critters in the capture of food. They have only one row of suckers. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
Lining both sides of the suckers you can see long slender muscular papillae (look closely towards the middle of this video!) ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
What do you think of these solar flare looking  beauties Nation? ⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
A profound THANK YOU to #NautilusLIVE team for exploring areas of the ocean that have never been explored before!  Hit the mail icon and share this video to your stories if ya wanna pass this information along! <3 <3 <3 ⁣⁣⁣⁣

Broadclub cuttlefish change colors faster than the human eye can blink (one fifth of one second!)

Cuttlefish reign supreme in that they have more color changing chromatophores per square inch on their skin than any squid or octopus!

In the first photo you can see thousands of pinpoint sized pigment cells… less than a second the cells expand and create what you see in the 2nd photo— a blushing cuttle! ☺️

Ready to learn? Let’s GO!  🎥 @whoi.ocean🥇  The Dumbo octopus cannot propel itself with jet propulsion like most octos. They rely solely on their strong muscular fins to help them swim through the deep-sea! 💪🐙
 🤓Before we get into it..let’s get geeky, shall we? 
🐙 Octopuses are divided into two suborders:   1️⃣ Cirrina/Cirrata - ‘Finned’ octopuses that have a small, internal shell and two fins on their head (ex. Dumbo, Flapjack)   2️⃣ Incirrina/Incirrata - No fins or internal shells (ex. common octopus, giant pacific octopus)   🦴 The small, internal “U” or saddle shaped shell supports the dumbos two big flappy fins on their head. (And yes, the nickname is based off of Disney’s Flying Elephant!)
⁣⁣⁣⁣
🥇 This species has the deepest known living cephalopod record — being spotted at 7,000m deep (4.35 miles deep!) ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⚠️ Cirroteuthis Muelleri is one of the largest cirrate octopuses, growing to a length of 1.5 metres (4.9 ft)⁣⁣
⁣⁣
🐘: so it’s basically a GIANT Dumbo Octopus! 🤩⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
👗 you’ve probably noticed that Cirrate octopuses have quite the dress! Observe how the webbing extends to the very tips of their arms! ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
🤩 The name Cirrate comes from the long slender hair-like structures called ‘cirri’ that MIGHT aid these critters in the capture of food.   🖋🚫 Cirrate octopuses are interestingly different from most other cephalopods in that they have NO Ink sacs (Explain yourself Pearl) and only one row of suckers with long slender hair-like structures on both sides.   The cirri on their arms are thought to play some role in feeding, as the currents created by them might help bring food closer to the beaks of these fascinating creatures of the deep!   DM us if you want to see a photo of the Cirri!
⁣⁣⁣⁣

Which fact surprises you the most? 📸: @mbari_news ⬇️
1️⃣ Seven-arm octopuses are one of the two largest, if not the largest, known species of octopus. Can you picture this octopus growing up to 11 feet (3.5m) and weighing in at 165 pounds (75kg) — UM…WHAT? 🤯

2️⃣ The 7-Arm #Octopus actually has 8 arms (surprise) But the male takes extra care in protecting his eighth arm — the mating arm, used to deliver sperm to a female. 
 Wildly enough, this special arm develops in an inconspicuous sack/pouch under their right eye. 

A small male will drift along until he meets a giant female, up to 20 times bigger than he is. Then he’ll break off his mating arm and give it to her so she can fertilize her eggs!
 3️⃣ The life span of 7-arm octopuses remains unknown at this time, however, it may have a relatively long life span to reach its large size (for instance giant octopuses live 3 to 5 years!)

4️⃣ In 30 years the Monterey Bay Aquarium deepwater research submersible has only seen this species five times total!  
5️⃣ Their depth range is thought to be between 0 m and 6,787 m (4.22 miles deep!) Yup…just casually hanging hanging out from freezing to warm water temperatures 
❄️🐙🔥  
6️⃣ They’re in the same family as the blanket octopus (Argonautoidea) remember how the blanket octopus uses the stinging tentacles of the man-o-war like nunchucks against predators? Well guess what— the 7 arm octo does the same! 
7️⃣ The 7-arm Octopus participates in the largest migration on earth in biomass and number of animals participating. It is called diel vertical migration and it’s an upwards migration in the evening and a downwards migration in the morning. We think they might come up during the night to get snacks & go back down during the evening to avoid predators!
 If ya read this far comment 🐙🤓 & let us know if ya learned anything 🧠

Caption this Video! 🐙vs 🐡
🎥 @videobubbles ⬇️❓
Stonefish Vs. Octopus
💀 You’re looking at the MOST venomous fish on this planet, the stonefish!⁣⁣⁣
⁣
🌊 When the tide goes out, these spiky blobs can hang out for 24 hours beneath the sand — ahh! 🤯

This would be cool if they didn’t ALSO have 13 hypodermic needle-like spines on their back that could easily penetrate your footwear! ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
💉 The venom contains verrucotoxin (VTX)  which can induce intense pain, respiratory weakness, damage to the cardiovascular system, convulsions and paralysis, and can lead to death. 

Saving Grace: 
stonefish anti-venom exists! (unlike the blue ring octopus)
⁣⁣⁣
🐙 The fearless day octopus doesn’t seem too concerned with this spicy meatball— it pounces on the stonefish, injects it’s venom paralyzing it instantly and then walks to a nearby den & begins to eat. ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
😋 Whelp, that’s that nation! 
⁣⁣⁣
📖 Read this far? Comment 🤓 🐙 and tell us what ya found most interesting- we love knowing who the super fans are! ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⚠️ (Honestly, we still can’t get over the idea of a stone fish spine going through a flip-flop- OUCH! — I found a photo of that if you’re interested)

What fascinates you most about the octopus? 🎥: @game_qmi 
👾 This is the cutest species most have NEVER heard of… the HAIRY Octopus! (So please share to your stories!) 

📎 The paperclip-sized Hairy Octopus has a round, fluffy-looking body with arms that twist and curl, making it look like an adorable PomPom ball! 🥲🐙

If an octopus were to ever star in a hair commercial– it would most definitely be this one! 🐙🤩

🌱 The branching hair-like skin is an incredible superpower of the Hairy Octopus that allows it to expertly camouflage in its environment. 

🧠 The fuzzy skin is called papillae and this cryptic species can control the size and projections– meaning– it controls how hairy it wants to appear (on demand!) 

⚠️ We just finished a blog that’ll tell ya way more info at OctoNation.com 

Photographer @game_qmi said it had been 5 years since he last encountered a hairy octopus (they’re extremely rare to spot due to their size) 

Till then, what do you think would be a good nickname for this tiny hairy octopus? 

We call em Chewbactopusses because they still haven’t been given a scientific name! 😂

Where are our CuttleFans at? ⁣🤩
🎥: @christoph_troesch_underwater ⁣
⁣ 🔎✨ Cuttlefish have more color changing chromatophores per square inch of their skin than any squid or octopus! 

They can also change colors faster than the human eye can blink (one fifth of one second!) Could you imagine having TV screen-like skin? 🤯⁣ ⁣⁣⁣⁣ Remarkable! 🤩

I’ve watched the final scene in this clip so many times as the last of the flamboyant cuttlefish vibrant colors completely vanish! 
⁣⁣⁣
The videographer said:⁣
⁣“The beauty is in the details! Watch closely how this awesome flamboyant cuttlefish (Metasepia pfefferi) changes its shape and colors in no time at all! Scientists still wonder how cephalopods are able to do this kind of camouflage as it is so fast and complex. We‘ve witnessed this scene at Air Bajo, Lembeh.🇮🇩⁣”

Read this far? Comment 120👾 - that’s how many different species of cuttlefish their are! CuttleNation or what? Lol 💙

Any Name Ideas for this beauty? 💜 
🌺 “Lavender Waves"🌊 
Fun Fact: Day Octopuses are living, breathing art with hundreds of thousands of coloring changing cells (chromatophores) in their skin— they are nature’s most incredible canvases (where no two pictures can ever be the same!)

Photographer @ernieblackphoto said,
“I have photographed the Day Octopus in Hawaii on multiple occasions, and have never seen anything like this. I was lucky enough to intercept this one as it was shooting across the shallows from one patch of reef to another,”

“Although it did not ink, after a quick dart to its left, it stopped and took on a flower shape. I can only assume this was in attempt to intimidate me.

This interaction only lasted a couple of seconds, before it went to blend in with the reef, leaving me amazed!”

This octopus behavior is referred to as deimatic or startle display— where an octopus puffs up its body as if to say — “hey human, I’m bigger than I look! Ok… im gonna leave now” 

You’ve seen this behavior before in other creatures that lack a strong defense— you know how butterflies have fake eye spots on their wings to appear intimidating?

Well look closely (zoom in) and you’ll see two dark oval eye spots being displayed here— isn’t it incredible how connected Mother Nature is? 

Have you heard of the Hawaiian day octopus before? 

Do you have a new favorite octopus now?

Is it just us, or is this relaxing to watch?😍⁣
🎥: @matthewunderwater 
💅 Did you know octopuses do their own manicures?  🤔 It might sound crazy, but hear us out. 

Octopus suckers have something called a ⁣⁣chitinous cuticle— it’s kinda like your finger nails, except for octopuses it’s a protective lining covering the surface of every-single sucker they have! 

Just like our fingernails make it easy for us to pick things up, an octopuses textured sucker lining helps them hold onto objects and not let go! 

What happens when your nails get too long? 
Ya bite em, trim em, or maybe even paint em!   When an octopuses sucker lining wears out, it will carefully begin to swirl it’s 8 arms together until all that's left is hundreds of round translucent sucker discs floating around its den.   The outgrown sucker lining sheds off revealing well-manicured squeaky clean suckers! Look at those pearly-whites! ✨🐙✨  And that’s not all folks…   Not only does grooming improve their grip strength, it sharpens their ability to taste and smell with the suckers on their arms! Wild huh?!
